[3] Brazil (Rio de Janeiro): 880 horses potentially exposed
Date: Wed 29 Jul 2015
Source: Folha de Sao Paulo [in Portuguese, trans. Mod.JW, edited]
http://www1.folha.uol.com.br/esporte/2015/07/1662123-as-vesperas-de-evento-teste-ja-sao-880-cavalos-do-rio-com-suspeita-de-doenca.shtml


The Ministry of Agriculture begins on Thu 30 Jul 2015 the 2nd blood draw in Rio horses [potentially exposed to] glanders, an incurable disease transmitted by bacteria that can infect humans. In total, 880 horses are suspected [more likely this is the number of horses exposed - Mod.TG] of having the disease in the city.

As Folha revealed on [Wed 22 Jul 2015], the government suspended the termination of 45 animals suspected of having the same illness at the Army Equitation School in the Deodoro zone west of Rio. There, in all 584 horses are [contacts]. Besides these animals at the Deodoro school, which will host the equestrian test event of Rio-2016 from [6 Aug 2015], another 96 police and military horses and 250 horses of SHB (Brazilian Equestrian Society) have been [exposed to the] disease.

Despite the number, the Ministry of Agriculture does not characterize it as an epidemic and, yes, as a preventive action. According to Folha newspaper, the investigation began after a horse that was in Deodoro between February and November 2014, was diagnosed with glanders in February this 2015. As a result, all horses that may have had contact with the infected horse are being investigated.

In February [2015], 2 horses in Deodoro expressed disease and they were referred to the Cananea Island Quarantine Station, where scientific studies of the disease will be conducted followed by termination of the animals. Currently at the base there are 17 infected horses.

Sought by Folha, the SHB said glanders tests are conducted periodically, every 60 days, by the institution and that the measure taken by the ministry is only preventive. The elite Rio club has the most expensive horses in the city, some valued at BR one million [USD 300 000]. Already the military police said that animals suspected of [exposure to] the disease are isolated and awaiting the [test] results from the Ministry of Agriculture.

Sought by Folha, the International Equestrian Federation said it was advised of the case of possible contamination of glanders, but trusts the Ministry of Agriculture for effective sanitary isolation of the test event. The threat of contamination by the Army horses occurs close to the day of the equestrian test event of the [Rio] Olympic Games in 2016, which will receive national competition horses. The Riding School is 350 meters [0.2 mi] away [550 m according to the report in [2] above], while international protocol determines a minimum radius of 200 meters [0.12 mi] from the event area.

The 1st blood sample from the animals was taken between 3 and 14 Jul 2015, in all 584 horses in the Deodoro Complex, where the school is located. According to military information, the ministry had informed that these animals showed 17 positive results for the disease; another 18 were inconclusive. Because of the collection, the Army rented stalls to separate the animals suspected of the disease. They were assembled outside the school, near the main pedestrian access. The move there is [to make sure that there is] no possibility of contamination of other animal sites.

According to the military, the ministry came to warn the school verbally that 45 horses would be terminated on 22 Jul 2015, because of the proximity to the test event. Therefore, the command Army ordered ditches to be dug to bury the animals, according to an official report to the Folha. The animals would be killed humanely. The same day, Army officials questioned the test because it considered it flawed and, in a meeting between the Ministry of Agriculture and the military, it was decided that a new trial [had to be] done. One day after the meeting, the Ministry of Agriculture confirmed the information [that there would be] a new test.

At the request of the military, [blood] will be sent for analysis with a total of 3 test batteries at a laboratory in Germany, since Ministry of Agriculture laboratories do not yet have an international standard certificate. The result of the 3 batteries should be released in October 2015. [This seems a bit late for the event. - Mod.JW]

[Byline: Bruna Fantti]

